SIMPLE: streak
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Streak
<hw>Streak</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Stretch</er>, <er>Streek</er>.]</ety> <def>To stretch; to extend;
hence, to lay out, as a dead body.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng. &
Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Streak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Streak
<hw>Streak</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>streke</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>streek</ets> a line, stroke, G. <ets>strich</ets>, AS.
<ets>strica</ets>, Sw. <ets>strek</ets>, Dan. <ets>streg</ets>, Goth.
<ets>stricks</ets>, and E. <ets>strike</ets>, <ets>stroke</ets>. See
<er>Strike</er>, <er>Stroke</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Strake</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A line or long mark of a
different color from the ground; a stripe; a vein.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What mean those colored <qex>streaks</qex> in heaven?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>A strake.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>The fine powder or mark yielded by
a mineral when scratched or rubbed against a harder surface, the color
of which is sometimes a distinguishing character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The rung or round of a ladder.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Streak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Streak
<hw>Streak</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Streaked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Streaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form streaks or
stripes in or on; to stripe; to variegate with lines of a different
color, or of different colors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A mule . . . <qex>streaked</qex> and dappled with white and
black.</q> <rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>streaked</qex> and glowing with the morning red.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>With <xex>it</xex> as an object: To run
swiftly.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Streaked</ent>⟦br⟧
